Sweet! Because
we are subtracting a square from another square, we can use the difference of squares formula, which is $x^2 - y^2 = (x + y)(x - y)$.
In this case, $x = 28$ and $y = 16$. So
\begin{align*}
28^2 - 16^2 &= (28 + 16)(28 - 16)\\
&=\boxed{4 \cdot 12 = 48}.
\end{align*}
The reason we used $x + y$ and $x - y$ instead of just $x$ and $y$ is because $x^2 - y^2$ is equal to $(x + y)(x - y)$. That way we take the same "average" of $x$ and $y$ twice, once with addition and once with subtraction. It makes the product easier to work with. I hope that helps!
